we always should review our code on stage area before commiting
it's whole purpose of stage area!
for this we need exact line of code that we have staged.
for this we use "diff" command
usually we don't use terminal to comparing code!
but just to see how is it, we want to compare our pre stage (that exist on production)
with our new stage that we want to commit it.

1.git diff --staged (staged changes)
  it's comparing current stage with "head" (last commit)
  in other word we want to see what happened by commiting

git break our changes to some chunks, so we can review them easily
so we can see changes if we have some changes on some different files

1.1: at first of each chunk, he specify the file that he want to compare like:
     diff --git a/src/section_2/viewing staged and unstaged changes 10 b/src/section_2/viewing staged and unstaged changes 10
     (file a: a is the file that we commit last time
      file b: b is the file we have on stage now )

1.2: then we have legend!
     --- /dev/null
     +++ b/src/section_2/viewing staged and unstaged changes 10
     it's introduce that  --- is for old code
                          +++ is for new code

Note: because we add a new file
      old code is null!

1.3: the we have header
     @@ -0,0 +1,11 @@
     it want to represent what part of these files is comparing
     in this chunk!
     - means old file (from line 0, bring 0 line on old file
                       because it don't exist)
     + means new file (from line 1, bring 11 lines on new file)

Note: +/- is not about adding or removing lines!
      it's about old or new line
      adding/removing represent by color
      if we remove some line on ore new code:
      + (red line)

-----------------------------------

2.git diff (unstaged changes)
  if we have some changes on working directory
  and we want to compare it to stage area before adding it to stage
  we should simply use "git diff "


